<h2 class="bold font-l">Assassin's Creed II</h2>
<p class="_pmvv-vidbox-descTxt">
At least from Desmond's point-of-view; the first thing you do in this game is snap out of Eagle Vision, said ability being the last thing Desmond used before the first game abruptly ended. </p>
<p class='example_row'>Example of:<br><a href="/pmwiki/pmwiki.php/Main/ImmediateSequel" class='trope-example-link'>Immediate Sequel</a></p>
</div>
<div class="video-examples-thumbs">
<a href="#video-link" data-video-id="jlue3h" data-video-descrip="Le Parkour-like moves appear in the action platformer Assassin's Creed I and are practically the game's main selling point. Which is sensible, given that it's from the team responsible for the Prince of Persia examples above. While it's called free-running (thus not making the distinction on this page's main article), in general the player characters practice Parkour whenever they need to get around quickly, and the game's racing/courier missions tend to enforce efficiency as the focus. Strangely enough though, somehow every Thief, Agile guard, Robber and Borgia Courier seems to practice Parkour, and Francesco de' Pazzi demonstrates amazing proficiency for a presumably non-athletic man, much less a non-Assassin. (It's implied that for the player characters, their physical aptitude is a &amp;quot;family thing.&amp;quot;)" data-video-title="Assassin's Creed I" data-video-url="https://d1w6li7s85ibls.cloudfront.net/qvbr/jlue3h_640x360p_qvbr.mp4" data-video-thumbnail="https://static.tvtropes.org/trope_videos_transcoded/images/sd/jlue3h.jpg" data-video-trope="Main/LeParkour" data-video-tropename="Le Parkour" data-video-approval="APPROVED" data-video-troper-rating="" data-video-average-rating="" data-video-rating-count="" data-video-media-sources="VideoGame/AssassinsCreedI" class="video-launch-link video-overlay-link video-background-image lazy-image" data-src="https://static.tvtropes.org/trope_videos_transcoded/images/sd/jlue3h.jpg">
<p><span class="bold">Assassin's Creed I</span></p>
</a>
<a href="#video-link" data-video-id="ypbtw2" data-video-descrip="The Apple of Eden are sphere-shaped pieces of technology created by the Isu. Having long outlived their creators, the Apples are featured prominently, although cryptically, throughout recorded history as the cause of several 'divine' and 'superhuman' events; these include the Trojan War, the parting of the Red Sea, and Adam and Eve being cast out of Eden." data-video-title="The Apple of Eden" data-video-url="https://d1w6li7s85ibls.cloudfront.net/qvbr/ypbtw2_640x360p_qvbr.mp4" data-video-thumbnail="https://static.tvtropes.org/trope_videos_transcoded/images/sd/ypbtw2.jpg" data-video-trope="Main/LostTechnology" data-video-tropename="Lost Technology" data-video-approval="APPROVED" data-video-troper-rating="" data-video-average-rating="" data-video-rating-count="" data-video-media-sources="VideoGame/AssassinsCreedI" class="video-launch-link video-overlay-link video-background-image lazy-image" data-src="https://static.tvtropes.org/trope_videos_transcoded/images/sd/ypbtw2.jpg">
<p><span class="bold">The Apple of Eden</span></p>
</a>
